Commands

There are five types :

  • data
  • operators
  • variables
  • functions
  • keywords

Numeric

example(integer)

integr> ## as.integer() truncates:
integr> x <- pi * c(-1:1, 10)

integr> as.integer(x)
[1] -3  0  3 31

integr> is.integer(1) # is FALSE !
[1] FALSE

integr> is.wholenumber <-
integr+     function(x, tol = .Machine$double.eps^0.5)  abs(x - round(x)) < tol

integr> is.wholenumber(1) # is TRUE
[1] TRUE

integr> (x <- seq(1, 5, by = 0.5) )
[1] 1.0 1.5 2.0 2.5 3.0 3.5 4.0 4.5 5.0

integr> is.wholenumber( x ) #-->  TRUE FALSE TRUE ...
[1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
?double
?numeric

Characters

b <- "unil"
c <- "patient 1"
nchar(b)
[1] 4
nchar(c)
[1] 9
paste(b, c, collapse = "")
[1] "unil patient 1"

Logical elements

  • TRUE et FALSE

and also…

  • NA, NaN
  • Inf
1/0
[1] Inf
x <- Inf
x - x
[1] NaN

“NA” means “Not available”.

“NaN” means “Not a Number”.

Operators

Arithmetic operators

  • +
  • -
  • *
  • /
  • ˆ
  • %%
  • %/%
  • %*%

Operators for comparisons

1 == 1
[1] TRUE
1 == 2
[1] FALSE
1 != 1 
[1] FALSE
1 != 2
[1] TRUE
1 < 1
[1] FALSE
1 <= 1
[1] TRUE

Logical operators

a <- (1 < 2)
a
[1] TRUE
!a
[1] FALSE
b <- (2 > 3)
a & b
[1] FALSE
a | b
[1] TRUE

How to know the type of data ?

a <- 1
b <- 1:5
class(a)
[1] "numeric"
class(b)
[1] "integer"
c <- "hello"
d <- 1 > 2
class(c)
[1] "character"
class(d)
[1] "logical"

What are their sizes ?

length(a)
[1] 1
length(b)
[1] 5
length(c)
[1] 1
length(d)
[1] 1

str gives a description.

str(a)
 num 1
str(b)
 int [1:5] 1 2 3 4 5
str(c)
 chr "hello"
str(d)
 logi FALSE

Variables

Here, a and b are variables.

a <- 1
b <- 2
a + b
[1] 3

=, <- and -> are assignement operators. They are used to save data.

?'<-'

Classes

  • Vectors
  • Lists
  • Matrices
  • Tables
  • Data frames

Vectors

x <- c(5,4,5,6,7,8) 
x
[1] 5 4 5 6 7 8
x_char = c("a","b","c") 
x_char
[1] "a" "b" "c"

Access elements of a vector

x
[1] 5 4 5 6 7 8
x[2]
[1] 4
x[c(2,4)]
[1] 4 6
x[c(-2,-4)]
[1] 5 5 7 8

Manipulate them…

x[6] = 10
x
[1]  5  4  5  6  7 10
a = c(3,4,5,6)
a[c(2,3)] = 0
a
[1] 3 0 0 6
a[c(2,3)] = c(8,7)
a
[1] 3 8 7 6
c(1,2,3) + c(3,4,5)
[1] 4 6 8
4 * c(1,2,3)
[1]  4  8 12
c(2,5) < 4
[1]  TRUE FALSE
c(1,2) + c(3,4,5,6)
[1] 4 6 6 8

… but watch out.

c(1,2) + c(2,3,4)
longer object length is not a multiple of shorter object length
[1] 3 5 5

Data frames

  • Write in R console: help(package="magrittr")
  • Choose “User guides, package vignettes and other documentation.”
  • Open the vignette magrittr::magrittr

The following example is taken from there.

library(magrittr)
  mtcars %>%
  subset(hp > 100) %>%
  aggregate(. ~ cyl, data = ., FUN = . %>% mean %>% round(2)) %>%
  transform(kpl = mpg %>% multiply_by(0.4251)) %>%
  print
mtcars
mtcars %>%
  subset(hp > 100)
